 First, let's evaluate $f(2)$:
\begin{align*}
f(2) &= 2^2 + 2\sqrt{2} \\
&= 4 + 2\sqrt{2} \\
\end{align*}
Now, let's evaluate $f(8)$:
\begin{align*}
f(8) &= 8^2 + 2\sqrt{8} \\
&= 64 + 2(2\sqrt{2}) \\
&= 64 + 4\sqrt{2} \\
\end{align*}
Thus, $2f(2) - f(8)$ becomes:
\begin{align*}
2f(2) - f(8) &= 2(4 + 2\sqrt{2}) - (64 + 4\sqrt{2}))\\
&= 8 + 4\sqrt{2} - 64 - 4\sqrt{2} \\
&= \boxed{-56}. \\
\end{align*}
